amdgpu: ps4_sbl — SAMU mailbox primitives + debugfs probe (SBL Phase 1)

First piece of the Sony SBL port: the synchronous SMU read/write through
the SAMU mailbox. Decoded from sceSblDriverReadSmuIx/WriteSmuIx via
Ghidra (FUN_c89b80b0 / FUN_c89b81d0); details in
checkpoint/docs/research/sbl-port/PLAN.md and
checkpoint/docs/research/orbis-dungeon/rooms/sbl-driver.md.

What this iteration tests:

    Does the SAMU respond to Linux mailbox writes at all?

If yes, Sony's boot-time init is enough and we have a working primitive
to build the rest of the SBL on (Phase 2: async CCP, IRQ 0x98, workspace
buffer; Phase 3: program GFX SMU clocks; Phase 4: wire amdgpu calls
back into uvd_v4_2/vce_v2_0 so they stop soft-failing).

If no, the SAMU is likely waiting on auth or on a state we'd have to
replicate via sceSblDriverInitialize. That answer informs the next dig.

Surface (no kernel changes other than the probe):
  /sys/kernel/debug/dri/0/ps4_sbl_smu
    write 'R <hex_idx>'         -> issue SBL_SMU_READ
    write 'W <hex_idx> <hex_v>' -> issue SBL_SMU_WRITE
    read                        -> last op detail (op/idx/val/status/rc/poll_us)

Synchronous polling (udelay-1us, 100 ms timeout). No IRQ, no async
kthread, no workspace BO yet — those are Phase 2+.

MMIO interpretation caveat: Sony's samu_write/read uses *(base + off)
with base = *(DAT_ca726878 + 0x10), and we don't have the Ghidra decode
of the inner helper. We treat off as a byte offset into adev->rmmio
(BAR5 on CIK). If that's wrong the probe will time out or return all
0xFFFFFFFFs — that's the signal to revisit the BAR choice.

Cost: 1 new file (~290 lines), 1 Makefile line, 1 #ifdef hook in
amdgpu_debugfs_init. CONFIG_X86_PS4 gates everything.

Signed-off-by: Meerzulee <mirzaali@screeninternational.org>

